<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Asad Receives Yemen's al-'Attas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Asad Receives Yemen's al-'Attas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2705180894 Damascus Syrian Arab Television Network in 
Arabic 1730 GMT 27 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2705180894 </F>
<F P=104>  Damascus Syrian Arab Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Hafiz al-Asad received Haydar Abu-Bakr 
al-'Attas, former Yemeni prime minister and envoy of 'Ali Salim 
al-Bid, secretary general of the Yemeni Socialist Party, 
accompanied by 'Abd-al-Qawi Makkawi and Dr. 'Abd-al-'Aziz 
al-Dali, at 1130 today. Foreign Minister Faruq al-Shar' attended 
the meeting. 
  Talks dealt with the situation in Yemen and its regrettable 
developments, as well as the current efforts to address it. The 
talks also dealt with the impact of this situation on sisterly 
Yemen and its future as well as on the pan-Arab interest of the 
Arab nation. 
  The president emphasized to the Yemeni delegation that Syria 
is concerned about what is taking place in Yemen and is 
anxiously following the bloody developments that replaced 
brotherly dialogue in addressing differences. The president 
said fighting is not in the interest of the fraternal Yemeni 
people, the Arab nation, or the unionist aspirations of the Arab 
masses. The president said Syria renews its appeal to the 
Yemeni brothers to stop resorting to arms and blood, apply 
logic, observe national and pan-Arab interests, and return to 
constructive brotherly dialogue out of concern for Yemen and its 
unity -- land and people. 
  The Yemeni delegation expressed its appreciation for Syria's 
pan-Arab position. 
  Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas and his delegation left Damascus 
this evening following a two-day visit. Foreign Minister Faruq 
al-Shar' saw them off at Damascus International Airport. 
  In a statement to the Syrian Arab News Agency, al-'Attas 
said: Today, we were honored to be received by President Hafiz 
al-Asad. We were pleased by the positive stand of sisterly Syria 
and by the accurate analysis of the current situation in Yemen. 
Viewpoints were completely identical on the danger posed by the 
continuation of war in Yemen. This war threatens Yemen as well 
as the Arab nation and the region with numerous dangers. 
Therefore, we agreed to exert efforts and work together to stop 
the war and deal with all differences peacefully. 
  Asked about halting fighting and preserving Yemeni unity, he 
said: This is what we are working for. I think the mission on 
which we have to work, along with brothers in Syria and all 
brothers and friends, is that of stopping the war. By stopping 
the war, we can deal with all issues and preserve what remains 
of Yemen and safeguard its unionist march. 
  Responding to a question on the presence of contacts between 
Aden and Sanaa, he said: There are no contacts at present, 
except for those held through brothers and friends and the Arab 
League. 
  Al-'Attas described his visit to Damascus by saying: It was 
a visit we highly value because I sensed a positive stand of 
solidarity and an accurate analysis of the situation in our 
country as a result of the recently-declared war. 
  Al-'Attas welcomed all mediation and efforts to stop the war 
and avert further Yemeni losses and address the situation 
peacefully. He said: We welcomed the Egyptian mediation and the 
Egyptian-Emirian mediation and we welcome every mediation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

