<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jericho Closure Said Due to Large Hamas Rally </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jericho Closure Said Due to Large Hamas Rally </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA3005184494 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1700 GMT 30 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA3005184494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1700 GMT 30 May 94 </F>

<F P=105> Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Yoram Kohen] </F>
  [Text] A closure was imposed today on Jericho. Major 
General Ilan Biran, commander of the Central Command, decided to 
ban Israelis from entering the city until further notice. Our 
Army affairs correspondent Alon Ben-David reports that Hamas 
[Islamic Resistance Movement] was scheduled to hold a rally in 
the city this evening and the IDF [Israel Defense Forces] was 
worried about possible terror attacks. Earlier today Hamas 
staged a few processions in the city. Yoram Kohen reports: 
  [Begin Kohen recording] Today's procession in Jericho was a 
first test. Most participants came from outside the city, from 
Gaza and the West Bank. Hamas leaders in the territories sent 
hundreds of supporters to Jericho, seemingly to test the 
patience of the Palestinian police commanders. A similar 
demonstration was held recently in Gaza. 
  The Hamas rally started with a procession bearing 
provocative 
religious symbols, Koran books, and green flags, and marchers 
proudly chanting: 'Izz-al-Din al-Qassam is our mentor. The 
Palestinian police commanders explained their decision to allow 
Hamas to hold the rally in Jericho's big mosque by saying that 
theirs was a democratic society which did not shut people up, 
perhaps out of a wish to avoid confrontations. 
  Such a concentration of Hamas members in the self-rule area 
led Maj. Gen. Biran to take precautions. Consequently, he 
banned Israelis from entering the city until further notice. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

