Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Nepal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pakistan's Bhutto Pays Official Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pakistan's Bhutto Pays Official Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Holds Talks With Koirala </H4>

<F P=102> BK2505161394 Islamabad PTV Television Network in English 
1400 GMT 25 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2505161394 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PTV Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Formal talks between the prime minister, Ms. 
Benazir Bhutto, and the Nepalese prime minister, Mr. Girija 
Prasad Koirla, were held at the Singhe Darbar in Kathmandu 
today. The talks, which lasted over 90 minutes, were held in an 
atmosphere of cordiality, reminiscent of constructive and 
meaningful cooperation existing between Pakistan and Nepal. 
Pakistan Television's representative, Abdul Wahid, reports from 
Kathmandu that regional and international issues, including 
Kashmir, figured in the talks. 
  The two leaders also discussed bilateral relations with 
particular emphasis on economic cooperation. They agreed on 
steps to enhance cooperation in several fields, including trade 
and culture. Ms. Benazir Bhutto was assisted by the foreign 
minister, Sardar Asif Ahmad Ali; the minister of state for 
finance, Maqdum Shahabuddin; Special assistant to the prime 
minister on social sector, Begum Shahnaz Wazir Ali; the foreign 
secretary, Mr. Najmuddin Sheikh; and Pakistan's ambassador to 
Nepal, Mr. Mohammad Nasir Mian. The Nepalese prime minister, 
Mr. Girija Prasad Koirala, was assisted by a high-level team 
which included some cabinet ministers and economic experts. 
  Talking to newsmen after the talks, Ms. Benazir Bhutto 
described her discussions with the Nepalese prime minister as 
useful. 
  [Begin Bhutto recording] We discussed regional and 
international issues. And we also discussed how to improve 
cooperation. We must be holding the joint commission on an 
annual basis and we are also going to be holding an industrial 
exhibition here. So, Nepali businessmen can see what goods we 
have in Pakistan and we are going to have a cultural exchange 
office for (?our two nations). [end recording] 
  Speaking at a civic reception hosted by the citizens of 
Kathmandu this afternoon, the prime minister stressed the need 
of devotion and hard work for the economic uplift in the 
developing country. A very warm and colorful reception was 
extended to the prime minister and members of her entourage when 
they arrived at the Municipal Hall. The mayor of Kathmandu, Mr. 
P.L. Singh, greeted the distinguished guests. The prime 
minister was profusely garlanded. The prime minister was 
enthusiastically greeted as she entered the hall. The mayor of 
Kathmandu welcomed the prime minister on her historic visit. 
The mayor then presented the key of Kathmandu city to the prime 
minister. Speaking on the occasion, Ms. Benazir Bhutto said the 
people of Pakistan and Nepal who are fellow members of SAARC 
[South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation] countries 
have common struggle for parliamentary democracy and democratic 
institutions. She reminded that the population living in the 
developing countries have to strive for achieving the cherished 
goals of economic betterment of their masses. She thanked the 
people of Kathmandu for extending a rousing reception to her and 
the members of her delegation and said this reflects the 
sentiments of Nepalese people for their Pakistani brethren. 
  The president of the Nepalese Congress, Mr. Krishnanath 
Prasad Bhattarai, called on the prime minister, Ms. Benazir 
Bhutto, in Kathmandu yesterday. During the meeting, the prime 
minister briefed the president of the Nepalese Congress about 
the democratic process in Pakistan. The prime minister also 
reiterated the unflinching commitment of her government for 
democracy and the growth of democratic institutions. She said 
her government is also undertaking steps to bring positive 
changes in the socioeconomic structure of her country. Mr. 
Bhattarai paid tributes to the prime minister for her struggle 
for democracy and the rule of law. 
  The chairman of the Communist Party of Nepal and the leader 
of the opposition in the Nepalese parliament, Mr. Manmohan 
Adhikari, also called on the prime minister, Ms. Benazir Bhutto, 
in Kathmandu. The leader of the Nepalese opposition lauded the 
prime minister of Pakistan for her deep commitment toward 
democracy and human rights. The prime minister, while 
reciprocating the gesture, informed the Nepalese leader that 
Pakistan wants to see democracy in South Asia and the growth of 
human rights in the region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

