<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-104 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Nepal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pakistan's Bhutto Pays Official Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pakistan's Bhutto Pays Official Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Addresses News Conference, Departs </H4>

<F P=102> BK2705030894 Islamabad PTV Television Network in English 
1400 GMT 26 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2705030894 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PTV Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The prime minister, Ms. Benazir Bhutto, has said 
the resolution of the Kashmir issue is vital to complete the 
charter of the Pak-India partition plan. She was addressing a 
news conference in Kathmandu this afternoon prior to her 
departure for home. Replying to a question on plebiscite in 
Kashmir, the prime minister said: 
  [Begin Bhutto recording] (?Already) Pakistan made its demand 
for plebiscite. And you know who else agreed to plebiscite? 
Prime Minister Jawaharlal Nehru of India. And you know who 
else agreed to plebiscite? The entire international community 
in the United Nations. So what we are saying is that why this 
subcontinent gives rapt attention just because India and 
Pakistan cannot deal with the problem which we have inherited 
from partition. [sentence as heard] So, we are saying let us 
solve that. Let us solve that under the Simla agreement and let 
us in the light of UN resolution (?if we cannot do it 
bilaterally). So let us do it multilaterally, but let us find a 
political solution. I noted the Indian scene that this is the 
Pakistani inspired uprising. But that is not so. There is no 
difference in this uprising than the difference wherein the 
people of Nepal rose up against the Rana rulers, for instance. 
So nobody can quench the desire of freedom because it is the 
part of the way I think; it is the people of a country or the 
people of a society. [sentence as heard] If they rise up, 
nobody can do anything about it. [end recording] 
  To another question, she said her visit to Nepal will herald 
a new era of cooperation between Pakistan and Nepal. 
  A warm send off was given to the prime minister when she 
left 
Kathmandu today for Islamabad. The Nepalese prime minister, Mr. 
Girija Prasad Koirala, bade farewell to Ms. Benazir Bhutto at 
the Tribhuvan Airport. Also present to see off the prime 
minister of Pakistan were members of the Nepalese cabinet, the 
mayor of Kathmandu, senior officials of the government, 
diplomats based in the Nepalese capital, and members of the 
Pakistani community. An impressive guard of honor was presented 
to Ms. Benazir Bhutto. National anthems of the two countries 
were also played on the occasion. Before boarding the aircraft, 
the prime minister and members of her entourage deeply thanked 
the Nepalese prime minister and other officials of his 
government for the warm hospitality during their stay in 
Kathmandu. 
  The prime minister, Ms. Benazir Bhutto, called on his 
majesty 
King Birendra of Nepal at Narenhiti Royal Palace in Kathmandu 
last night. The talks between his majesty and the prime 
minister lasted over half an hour. Later, King Birendra hosted 
a dinner in honor of Ms. Benazir Bhutto at the palace. The 
dinner was also attended by Queen Aishwarya; the prime minister 
of Nepal, Mr. Girija Prasad Koirala; and members of the prime 
minister's entourage. 
  The prime minister is now back in Islamabad. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-35246 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes104_v_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-104 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bhutto on Nuclear Inspections, Ties With U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bhutto on Nuclear Inspections, Ties With U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2705120194 Karachi DAWN in English 27 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> BK2705120194 </F>
<F P=104>  Karachi DAWN </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Islamabad, May 26 -- Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto 
said on Thursday that Islamabad had given counter proposals in 
response to U.S. suggestion that Pakistan should allow 
non-intrusive inspection of its nuclear installations. 
  "The question of non-intrusive inspection is an American 
proposal and we have given counter-proposals based on a regional 
solution," Ms Bhutto said at a news conference on her return 
from Nepal. 
  She was asked to comment on a recent statement of Foreign 
Minister Sardar Assef Ahmed Ali in which he had said that 
Pakistan was ready to allow non-intrusive inspection of its 
nuclear installations. 
  Denying that the foreign ministor had made any such offer, 
she said: "Pakistan will not accept any uniluteral solution or 
proposal." 
  Questioned whether President Farooq Ahmad Khan Leghari would 
be discussing the nuclear issue with American officials during 
his current visit to the United States, the Prime Minister said 
though the President's visit was a private one, "we are using 
this occasion to have informal talks with U.S. officials and to 
explain Pakistan's position on the nuclear issue." 
  Ms Bhutto said she would also be visiting the United States 
by the end of this year. "I hope it will be a substantive 
visit." 
  The Prime Minister said the Pressler Amendment, which debars 
Pakistan from getting U.S. military and economic aid, was a 
discriminatory law, "and we want it should go." 
  Ms Bhutto said Pakistan shared US concern over nuclear 
proliteration, "but we feel the Pressler Amendment is a veto in 
the hand of India." 
  She said Pakistan and the United States were cooperating in 
anti-narcotics campaign and defence of human rights, and added 
that the two could move in the nuclear non-proliferation field 
provided a regional approach on this issue was agreed upon. 
  Pakistan, she said, was anxious to improve its relations 
with 
the United States, but hastened to add that it did not want to 
do so just for having F-16 fighter aircraft. 
  "We don't want one-dimensional relationship. It should be a 
multi-dimensional one," she asserted. 
  Ms Bhutto said Pakistan had supported America during Soviet 
invasion of Afghanistan. "We have defended freedom in 
Afghanistan and we are cooperating with the United Nations in 
its peacekeeping preparations in Somalia and other parts of the 
world," she said, while calling for closer relationship between 
the two countries. 
  She said her government was building Pakistan as a modern 
Islamic state where rule of law would be supreme. She said a 
society would be built where women would have an equal role to 
play. A women's police station had already been set up and 
women's courts would also be established, she said. 
  Answering a question, Ms Bhutto said she wanted the 
opposition to cooperate with the government on three main issues 
-- Pakistan-U.S. relations, Pakistan-India ties and the nuclear 
issue. "On these three subjects we (the government and the 
opposition) should have a unified stand," she said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

