<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Lawzi on Arab Support, Political Settlement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Lawzi on Arab Support, Political Settlement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN3005100194 Amman SAWT AL-SHA'B in Arabic 30 May 94 pp 1, 20 </F>
<F P=103> JN3005100194 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman SAWT AL-SHA'B </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Lamis al-Barghuthi] </F>
  [Excerpts] Sanaa -- Yemeni Information Minister Hasan 
al-Lawzi has praised Jordan's role in the Yemeni crisis. He 
said that the stand adopted by Jordan --king, government and 
people -- is a principled stand based on the nation's interest 
in unity. [passage omitted] 
  On future prospects, the possibility of internationalizing 
the crisis, and on Arab countries' recognition of the secession, 
Dr. al-Lawzi said: I do not believe any Arab country will dare 
to publicly recognize the secession. [passage omitted] 
  Al-Lawzi said: If some try to create problems abroad for 
Yemeni unity and legitimacy then the situation will have to be 
expeditiously settled in a military manner no matter the cost. 
However, I have to say that there are signs of a political 
solution through reaching an understanding with the unionist 
elements within the Yemeni Socialist Party. This factor, in 
addition to the Yemeni command's desire to avoid large numbers 
of civilian casualties, postpones the military option. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-35302 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes104_j_94031" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-104 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Basindwah Issues Statement, Departs for Cairo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Basindwah Issues Statement, Departs for Cairo </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2805182994 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
1700 GMT 28 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2805182994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister brother Muhammad Salim Basindwah 
today left for Cairo on a visit to Egypt. He will convey a 
message from Lieutenant General brother 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih, 
Presidential Council chairman, to his brother President Husni 
Mubarak about relations between the two brotherly countries and 
Yemeni developments. Basindwah will also lead our country's 
delegation to meetings of foreign ministers of the Nonaligned 
Movement, set to convene in Cairo from 30 May to 4 June. 
  Before leaving Sanaa, the foreign minister told SABA' he 
will 
take the opportunity of his presence in the Egyptian capital and 
his attendance at the nonaligned conference to convey a true 
picture of what is going on in Yemen to as many ministers as 
possible. He will make the point that no one is out to force 
unity on others, because unity has been in place for four years. 
It must be made clear to the world that there is an attempt to 
force secession on the country and that some quarters try to 
misrepresent the situation. 
  The foreign minister hoped the nonaligned conference will 
produce beneficial decisions for the peoples of the movement. 
  The Yemeni delegation to the conference includes the under 
secretary for political affairs at the Foreign Ministry, and 
other ministry officials. 

</TEXT>

