<H3> <TI>   Al-Jifri Says No Contacts Made With Sanaa </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Jifri Says No Contacts Made With Sanaa </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA3105110594 Aden Democratic Republic of Yemen Radio Network 
in Arabic 0330 GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA3105110594 </F>
<F P=104>  Aden Democratic Republic of Yemen Radio Network 
in Arabic 0330 GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=105> Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement issued by 'Abd-al-Rahman 'Ali al-Jifri, vice </F>
chairman of the Presidential Council, to the YEMENI NEWS AGENCY 
in Aden; date not given] 
  [Text] The news media of the aggressive regime in Sanaa 
have made it a habit to broadcast statements from some of the 
regime's stooges about contacts the regime claims have been made 
with those it calls the unionists in the Yemeni Socialist Party 
[YSP] and saying that the totalitarian regime in Sanaa is on the 
brink of reaching agreement with them. We wish to categorically 
confirm the following: 
  In the YSP there are no unionists or separatists. All are 
unionists led by Brother President 'Ali Salim al-Bid who worked 
for unity and voluntarily signed the union agreement. The issue 
of contacts with any quarter whatsoever could only be legitimate 
if they are made with the official state establishments of the 
Democratic Republic of Yemen. The Sanaa regime has not made any 
such contacts with any state establishments of the Democratic 
Republic of Yemen. The YSP Political Bureau clarified this 
issue in an official statement issued on 28 April. 
  These allegations by the Sanaa regime are intended to cause 
confusion since that regime has failed militarily and 
politically to achieve its dreams of hegemony, domination, and 
occupation. We are not advocates of war but advocates of peace 
and shall defend the Democratic Republic of Yemen and the lives, 
possessions, and honor of its men and women, its people. We are 
able, God permitting, to do all this. 
  We support a permanent cease-fire to save our country and 
our 
brothers from destruction and bloodletting. This can be 
followed by negotiations between the Democratic Republic of 
Yemen and the Sanaa regime to define future relations between 
the two states. 
  We are advocates of unity but not on the basis of the former 
unity. When a regime emerges in Sanaa believing in justice, 
equal citizenship, human rights and all the ideals we cherish 
and contained in the pledge and accord document, we shall then 
discuss the issue of unity with that regime. 

</TEXT>

