<H3> <TI>   Parliament Extends State of Emergency 30 Days </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parliament Extends State of Emergency 30 Days </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0106133594 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
1200 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0106133594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] During the session it held this morning under 
Speaker Shaykh 'Abdallah Bin-Husayn al-Ahmar, the House of 
Representatives heard the letter addressed to it from Acting 
Prime Minister Dr. Muhammad Sa'id al-'Attar. 
  The letter reads: Brother Esteemed Speaker of the House of 
Representatives, Esteemed Members of the House of 
Representatives. May God's peace and blessing be upon you. The 
House of Representatives had earlier approved the declaration of 
the state of emergency in accordance with Republican Decree No. 
20 of 1994, which was necessitated by the internal sedition 
which was the result of the rebellion of secessionist elements 
in the Yemeni Socialist Party [YSP] leadership against the 
constitutional legitimacy, and the ensuing military actions and 
direct threat to the citizens' security and stability. Since 
the political leadership was concerned to make the period of the 
state of emergency very limited in harmony with the democratic 
policy of our country, the period was set for 30 days. However, 
the circumstances which necessitated the declaration of the 
state of emergency have not been finally settled. This calls 
for extending the state of emergency for another similar period. 
Based on Article 97 of the Constitution on the need to obtain 
the House of Representatives' approval for extending the state 
of emergency, we hope that the House will extend it for another 
30 days as of the end of the previous period, taking into 
consideration that the National Defense Council, which is 
entrusted with assessing the state of emergency, has approved 
such extension. In light of this, we present this request to 
your esteemed house. Please accept our greetings and 
appreciation. 
  The Parliament has agreed to extend the state of emergency 
for another 30 days in accordance with the public interest. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

