<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister on Cease-Fire, UN Intervention </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister on Cease-Fire, UN Intervention </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2905161494 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1515 GMT 29 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2905161494 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 29 May (MENA) -- Yemeni Foreign Minister 
Muhammad Salih Basindwah has said that Sanaa does not reject a 
cease-fire, but does not accept one based on the imposition of 
secession. Secession is impossible, he said. 
  In statements following his meeting with Arab League 
Secretary General Dr. 'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majd today, Basindwah said 
that as a condition for ending the fighting between Sanaa and 
Aden, legitimacy and the Constitution must be the standards. He 
stressed that all Yemenis defend unity and reject separation. 
  On 'Ali Salim al-Bid's request that south Yemen's Arab 
League 
membership be restored, Basindwah said the Arab League secretary 
general stressed to him that the request has no standing. 
  The Yemeni foreign minister denied that Iraqi or Sudanese 
forces are fighting alongside the Yemeni forces in the north. 
He said the southern allegations in this respect are false. 
Sanaa does not need fighters; it is Aden that needs additional 
forces, he said. 
  Basindwah said he informed Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid of the latest 
developments in Yemen. 
  He said events in Yemen prove that the "secessionists" 
cannot 
establish "their alleged state". 
  He said the head of the alleged state has fled to 
Hadhramaut, 
and will flee abroad from there. 
  He accused the southerners of providing shelter to world 
terrorist leaders, notably Marcos [name as received] and 
Abu-Nidal [Sabri al-Banna]. 
  Asked what Sanaa's position will be if the UN Security 
Council passes a resolution on the Yemeni crisis, Basindwah 
said: We oppose any interference in the crisis by the Security 
Council because this is an internal affair. 
  If the Security Council issues a resolution, he said, then 
we 
will react according to the situation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

