<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lebanese Foreign Minister Arrives for Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lebanese Foreign Minister Arrives for Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Al-Majali, Buwayz Discuss Ties </H4>

<F P=102> JN3005153394 Amman Radio Jordan Network in Arabic 1100 GMT 
30 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN3005153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Radio Jordan Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Dr. 'Abd-al-Salam al-Majali received 
at his office in the Prime Ministry today Lebanese Foreign 
Minister Faris Buwayz, who is participating in the 17th session 
of the Economic and Social Commission for Western Asia, ESCWA, 
which is currently convening in Amman. The talks dealt with 
ways to strengthen bilateral relations in all fields, 
particularly in the economic, trade, and customs fields. They 
also reviewed the latest developments in the peace process. 
  In a statement to PETRA after the meeting, Buwayz said he 
felt full readiness on the part of the prime minister to reach a 
new concept for Jordanian-Lebanese relations with the aim of 
developing cooperation and coordination between the two sisterly 
countries. He said: We, in Lebanon, greatly appreciate the 
fraternal Jordanian people. We have great interests with Jordan 
that need to be organized for the benefit of both countries and 
people. He stressed that the coming stage requires further 
coordination and cohesion toward the various issues. 
  Regarding the current Lebanese stand vis-a-vis the peace 
process, Buwayz said: Now that approximately three and a half 
years have passed since the Madrid conference, we cannot say 
that these talks have reached the sought level or achieved the 
sought results. We cannot also say that the Israeli side deals 
with these talks in the required way. New problems and 
challenges surfaced during this period. 
  Buwayz said: Despite all circumstances, we believe that this 
peace should be given a chance. We also believe that the 
Israeli side should prove it is still committed to the 
principles of peace in terms of its fairness and the 
implementation of the international resolutions and the 
principle of land for peace. 
  Regarding the most prominent developments in the trial of 
those accused of involvement in the assassination of Jordanian 
diplomat, martyr Na'ib al-Ma'ayitah, which began recently, the 
Lebanese foreign minister said: It is known that the competent 
Lebanese departments arrested the suspects moments after the 
crime was committed. We can say that Lebanese judiciary, which 
is known for its fairness and independence, will deal with this 
subject with all seriousness and it has issued the indictment. 
We have no doubt that the court will issue a fair decision. 
  The meeting was attended by Dr. Fawwaz Abu-al-Ghanam, 
minister of state and acting minister of state for foreign 
affairs, and the Lebanese ambassador in Amman. 

</TEXT>

