<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Majali, Yemeni Official Discuss Cease-Fire, UN </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Majali, Yemeni Official Discuss Cease-Fire, UN </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN3105130394 Amman Radio Jordan Network in Arabic 1100 GMT 
31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN3105130394 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Radio Jordan Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Dr. 'Abd-al-Salam al-Majali 
emphasized Jordan's firm position on the current situation in 
the Republic of Yemen and its support for the legitimacy and 
unity that was realized through agreement among all parties in 
the sisterly country. 
  At his meeting with 'Abd al-'Aziz 'Abd-al-Ghani, Yemeni 
Presidential Council member, at his office in the Prime Ministry 
this morning, the prime minister also emphasized the 
noninterference of Jordan in the Yemeni internal affairs, and 
Jordan's support for a cease-fire and a halt to fighting. 
  For his part, 'Abd-al-Ghani said in a statement to reporters 
that the meeting reviewed bilateral relations, the latest 
developments in the situation in the Republic of Yemen, and the 
visit he will make to the United States to attend the Security 
Council deliberations on the Yemeni crisis--a meeting called by 
certain countries. 
  He added: We are always ready for dialogue and diplomatic 
efforts to resolve the Yemeni crisis, and we are always ready to 
end fighting if the elements that created the situation return 
to constitutional legitimacy and retract the statement which 
sought--through armed rebellion--to separate parts of the 
Republic of Yemen formed on 22 May 1990, and blessed by all 
Yemeni people. 
  He added: We believe that discussing the issue at 
international forums is interference in Yemeni affairs because 
what is taking place in the Yemeni arena is a purely internal 
Yemeni affair. He said: What is taking place is a rebellion 
carried out by some elements of the Socialist Party that forced 
the constitutional legitimacy to confront it in order to realize 
security and stability in the Republic of Yemen. 
  Concerning the alternatives that may be proposed during the 
Security Council deliberations on this crisis, 'Abd-al-Ghani 
said the solution lies in resolving the issue in accordance with 
the constitutional legitimacy that resulted from the elections 
of March 1993, and--according to testimony of the whole 
world--were honest, and in which all eligible voters 
participated. 
  He added: We ask all brothers and friends to deal with the 
Republic of Yemen in accordance with the principles of 
international law which respect the sovereignty of every 
country, and state that no country should interfere in the 
affairs of another. 
  He emphasized that Yemeni unity is an accomplished fact 
supported by all Yemenis, and added that no one can return Yemen 
to the situation that prevailed before 22 May 1990. 
  He also stressed that the danger posed by presenting the 
Yemeni issue [at the Security Council] is the interference in an 
internal Yemeni affair. It is a serious step to discuss a 
subject that concerns a sovereign state and member of all 
regional organizations and the United Nations and one which is 
committed to the UN Charter and regional and international 
charters. 
  He added: We think that discussing any internal issue in any 
country is a dangerous precedent because doing so is not 
stipulated in the UN Charter, especially Article 2 of this 
charter. 
  The meeting was attended by Fawwaz Abu-al-Ghanam, acting 
minister of state for foreign affairs, and the Yemeni ambassador 
in Amman. 
  'Abd-al-Ghani left Amman for New York today. He was seen off 
by the acting minister of state for foreign affairs and the 
Yemeni ambassador in Amman. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

