<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Editorial Urges Closure of Orient House Offices </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Editorial Urges Closure of Orient House Offices </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA3105103294 Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT in Hebrew 31 May 94 p 
2 </F>

<F P=103> TA3105103294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "Jerusalem"] </F>
  [Text] Faysal al-Husayni, the autonomy's "minister on 
Jerusalem affairs," yesterday declared war for Jerusalem. He 
demands that "status quo" be preserved in the city and vows that 
Arabs will pursue their struggle for city control. He is not 
speaking of negotiations, he is speaking of control. Agreements 
are the last thing on his mind, and he is, as a matter of fact, 
saying precisely the same things his master 'Arafat did, 
although he is using more refined phrases. 
  His remarks are neither baloney nor poppycock. They demand a 
reaction, an immediate one. The required reaction is clear: 
The Orient House offices must be closed down, all PLO offices 
-- however they may be disguised or named -- must be moved from 
Jerusalem to Gaza or Jericho, and an unequivocal clarification 
must be issued -- in deed, not in words -- that the autonomy 
will not penetrate Jerusalem, either overtly or covertly. 
  As far as we are concerned, al-Husayni's remarks, too, are a 
call for jihad, a jihad without the commentators' smart-alecky 
interpretations. The only difference between the PLO head and 
his representative in Jerusalem is that 'Arafat made his remarks 
in Johannesburg, in what he believed was a closed setting. 
Al-Husayni dares make his statements in Jerusalem, striving to 
do it as publicly as possible. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

