<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin: U.S. Has Exhausted Its Role in Syrian Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rabin: U.S. Has Exhausted Its Role in Syrian Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA3105184694 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1700 GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA3105184694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1700 GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=105> Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Alon Ben-David] </F>
  [Excerpts] What is happening in the negotiations with 
Syria? Not much. Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin today dismissed 
as total nonsense reports that he had told Egyptian President 
Husni Mubarak that Israel would agree to implement a full 
withdrawal on the Golan Heights. Rabin was speaking before the 
Knesset Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee. Rabin added that 
in his opinion, the United States had exhausted its role in the 
negotiations with Syria and expressed the assessment that the 
talks in Washington would not resume. [passage omitted] 
  The prime minister opined that the Syrians would not 
continue 
the talks in Washington. Incidentally, Mr. Rabin said that the 
talks held in Washington so far had led to nothing. Rabin also 
sent a message to the Americans: I believe that Washington has 
already exhausted its role with regard to the Syrian track, he 
said. Israel, however, continues to have an interest in 
occasional visits by Secretary of State Warren Christopher. I 
am neither pessimistic nor optimistic, the prime minister 
concluded. 
  The Palestinian institutions in Jerusalem were also 
discussed 
at the session. We are currently preparing a list of all the 
Palestinian institutions and examining the issue not on the 
basis of goodwill but rather from the viewpoint of the legal 
measures at our disposal, Rabin said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

