<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Approves Plan To Lower Housing Costs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cabinet Approves Plan To Lower Housing Costs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2905153994 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 1500 GMT 29 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2905153994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The government today approved the joint Housing 
Ministry and Treasury plan to lower the cost of housing. This 
was after Housing Minister Binyamin Ben-Eli'ezer decided not to 
present his proposal for allocating contractors 51 percent of 
the land freed in return for building apartments for candidates 
eligible for mortgages. The government will meet again on 
Wednesday to discuss Ben-Eli'ezer's proposal. This is aimed at 
ensuring that contractors winning tenders allocate 25 percent of 
the land for apartments to those who have the right to Housing 
Ministry support. Harley Braidman reports: 
  [Begin recording] [Braidman] The government approved the 
joint Housing Ministry and Treasury plan of minimum state 
intervention in construction. The main point of the program is 
an article relating to the marketing of land. The Israel Land 
Administration and the Housing Ministry presented a clear 
detailed plan for marketing 50,000 units annually in the center 
of the country. Contracts will tie down builders to fixed dates 
for start and completion of construction to prevent them 
stocking up on plots. Finance Minister Avraham Shohat was 
pleased with the government's decision. 
  [Shohat] We think that we decided about the proper things to 
do, and I believe that in order to carry out a massive building 
program we are creating the proper environment to the market to 
start building. I believe that we made a proper decision. The 
main thing is that we got clear information about the amount of 
plots that are going to be sold on the market in order to build 
houses and this is quite a big number of 50,000 in 1994 and 
50,000 in 1995. I think that will reduce the cost of the 
apartments. 
  [Braidman] In addition to the 25,000 foreigners allowed in, 
the government approved 13,000 workers from the territories to 
return to construction in Israel. Planning procedures will be 
simplified and infrastructure work speeded up. The government 
will not return to budgetary purchase of flats nor promise to 
buy apartments in demand areas. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

