<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rao Commissions Indigenously Built Submarine </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rao Commissions Indigenously Built Submarine </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2905141694 Delhi Doordarshan Television Network in English 
1630 GMT 28 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2905141694 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi Doordarshan Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The prime minister has said funds for the 
indigenization program of the Indian Navy has been increased 
despite the reduction in the defense budget during the last few 
years. Mr. Narasimha Rao was speaking at the naval dockyard in 
Bombay today after commissioning the submarine INS [Indian Naval 
Ship] Shankul. The submarine has been built by the Mazagaon 
Docks Limited in collaboration with a German firm. Mr. Rao 
described the induction of INS Shankul -- the second 
indigenously built submarine -- as another landmark in maritime 
history of the country and its quest for self-reliance. The 
prime minister said the Indian Navy has been on the path of 
indigenization since the early 1980s and sustained, hard, and 
collaborative work has helped India reach the status of a 
submarine building nation. Mr. Rao said India's naval strength 
will essentially be for its self-defense and to protect its 
large offshore production assets -- fishing and exploitation of 
seabed resources -- in the exclusive economic zone. He said, we 
neither wish to control the ocean around us nor deny others 
their legitimate use or equitable access to the seas. 
  The chief of the Naval Staff, Admiral V.S. Shekhawat, 
accorded the acceptance of INS Shankul into the navy. The 
Maharashtra governor, Dr. P.C. Alexander, and the state chief 
minister, Mr. Sharad Pawar, were among those who attended the 
function. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

