Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Civilian Authority Begins To Exercise `Full Power' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Civilian Authority Begins To Exercise `Full Power' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0106172394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1530 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0106172394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Rafah, 1 Jun (MENA) -- The Palestinian civilian 
authorities have started to exercise their full power in the 
autonomy areas in Gaza and Jericho as of today. Staff Major 
General 'Abd-al-Raziq al-Majaydah, commander of the Palestinian 
National Security Forces, stated that a Palestinian-Israeli 
higher coordination committee has been formed and that three 
Palestinian liaison subcommittees were formed in Jericho, Gaza, 
and Khan Yunus to discuss outstanding matters and to come to a 
solution to the remaining problems that obstruct the 
implementation of the agreement, primarily the issue of borders 
and crossing points. 
  The autonomy areas have been divided into three zones, each 
entrusted to an official. They are North Gaza, from Wadi Gaza 
to Bayt Hanun, entrusted to Colonel Sulayman Halas; South Gaza, 
from Wadi Gaza to Rafah, entrusted to Brigadier General 
'Abd-al-Mu'ti al-Sab'awi; and Jericho, including the city of 
Jericho and camps, entrusted to Brigadier General Sa'id Naji. 
  Maj. Gen. al-Majaydah remarked that these appointments are 
temporary and are designed to run matters in the National 
Authority areas until Yasir 'Arafat completes his appointments. 
  In another development, a group of 222 Palestinian police of 
varying ranks from Tunis crossed the Rafah border point today. 
Another 600 individuals are expected to arrive from Libya this 
evening and a third group will arrive from Tunis in the next two 
days. 
  Meanwhile, the Hamas [Islamic Resistance Movement] and 
Islamic Jihad commands have decided to cooperate with the 
Palestinian National Authority on building the state, to abandon 
violence, and to form a political party to discuss matters 
objectively to serve the interests of the Palestinian people. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

