<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Ashrawi Explains Rejection of Information Portfolio </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Ashrawi Explains Rejection of Information Portfolio </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0206103494 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 2 Jun 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> PM0206103494 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "'Ashrawi Tells AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT: </F>
My Rejection of the Information Portfolio in the Authority is 
in Line With My Previous Positions"] 
  [Excerpts] Tunis, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- Dr. Hanan 'Ashrawi, 
former spokeswoman for the Palestinian delegation to Washington 
negotiations, has said that her refusal to assume the 
information ministry portfolio offered to her recently was in 
line with her previous position. 
  Replying to the numerous questions aroused by her 
participation in the authority council's meetings without being 
a member of it, 'Ashrawi told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT: From the 
outset I have chosen to lead the independent Palestinian 
committee for human rights. It was my commitment, especially as 
it is an agency working for the sake of achieving the 
Palestinian people's public welfare. 
  'Ashrawi said that "what is more important than holding 
posts 
and assuming portfolios is to agree on a foundation and a 
binding working program from which the National Authority 
Council's work proceeds." That is what prompted her to 
participate in its meetings and in drafting its program to 
ensure that the principles and aims binding on the authority 
council have been prepared and drafted by numerous people from 
among the Palestinian people. [passage omitted] 
  Responding to a statement by a Palestinian oppositionist, in 
which he said that in joining the authority council 'Ashrawi is 
exercising oneupmanship over the opposition, she said: "It has 
nothing to do with oneupmanship at all. I am not an 
oppositionist. Nor am I part of the authority. I am just part 
of society. And I believe that the language of oneupmanship 
have gone and been overtaken by events." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

