<H4>    Croatia's Granic on Ties With Bosnia </H4>

<F P=102> NC0106175794 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1215 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0106175794 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 1 Jun (MENA) -- Croatian Deputy Prime 
Minister and Minister of Foreign Affairs Mate Granic has 
declared that his country strongly supports a cease-fire in 
Bosnia-Hercegovina and a federation between Muslims and Croats. 
  At a press conference that he held today on the sidelines of 
the Non-Aligned Movement meeting in Cairo, the Croatian foreign 
minister said that Muslims and Croats have several things in 
common and that both are interested in establishing contacts and 
relations. He affirmed that no problems exist between the two 
sides and that they have an understanding and a type of 
cooperation between them. 
  Granic added that Croatia, one of the newest world states, 
is 
interested in building strong political and economic ties with 
different states. He noted that he seized the opportunity of 
his participation in the non-aligned meeting to hold over 200 
meetings with the foreign ministers at the conference to enhance 
bilateral ties and expand the scope of cooperation. 
  He noted that his country seeks to join the European Union 
[EU] and expects to sign an economic agreement with the EU by 
the end of the year. 

</TEXT>

