<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   11th Conference of Non-Aligned Countries Resumes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    11th Conference of Non-Aligned Countries Resumes </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Iran's Velayati on Denuclearization Issues </H4>

<F P=102> LD0206100194 Tehran IRNA in English 0929 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206100194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, June 2, IRNA -- Iranian Foreign Minister 'Ali 
Akbar Velayati here Wednesday [1 June] said that the non-aligned 
countries have traditionally demanded a time-bound framework, 
including a target date for removal and destruction of the 
entire stockpile of nuclear weapons. 
  Velayati, here for the 11th session of the Non-Aligned 
Movement (NAM) ministerial meeting, made the remark in his 
address to the NAM session on te issue of disarmament. 
  The issue of security assurances for non-nuclear weapon 
states is the second major point, Velayati said. 
  The non-aligned countries should insist that the 
Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) be finalized before the NPT 
review conference and that it should be comprehensive, 
verifiable, non-discriminatory and devoid of any 
exceptionalities. How to deal with the existing nuclear test 
sites also remains as an important task, he said. 
  In this respect, added Velayati, the non-aligned countries 
also welcome the decision of the [UN] General Assembly to start 
negotiations on a treaty banning the production of fissile 
materials for weapon purpose. 
  On the chemical weapons convention, he said that the 
non-aligned members of the Chemical Weapon Convention (CWC) need 
to consolidate their efforts to make certain that their views 
and positions on issues ranging from definition of chemical 
weapons and modalities of challenge inspection to the problem of 
technological assistance and peaceful use as well as their fair 
share in the organisation are met before ratification and 
entering into force of the convention. 
  As for biological weaapons, Velayati said that what may be 
at 
stake is the health requirements of the developing countries as 
significant parts of the pharmaceutical industry, including 
serum and vaccine production, will be affected by discussions 
due to take place at the special conference in September this 
year. 
  Touching on the issue of transparency in armament, the 
Iranian foreign minister said debate continues on the scope and 
expansion of the register. 
  "It is realized that regional arrangements is an essential 
ingredient for a complete register and, therefore, for the 
success of transparency in armament. This may also open the way 
for the reduction of conventional weapons both at regional and 
global levels to the eventual point of ensuring only the minimum 
security requirements of each state." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

